segments.text: I think you have to separate the two.
I think there's a life at sea for the people who enjoy getting away, who enjoy discovering these things as they come about, and there's certainly the role for people who don't have time for this.
And I have no objection to
to modelers that haven't been at sea, provided they have done their homework and they know what is known about the ocean in the literature.
And I think this will continue.
There's a lot more work that has to be done at sea, and there's a particular type of individual that enjoys doing this and prefers to do it above other things.
And I think that the modeler, it certainly does him good to be exposed to it because he

becomes a little more tolerant as to why there isn't the extensive database he needs, or when he says, I would like a set of observations across the Pacific at 10-mile intervals that he knows exactly the manpower and the cost and the difficulty that it does take to get it, and perhaps even the possibility of getting it in the time frame that he wants.
But I think that...
As I say, if a person has done his homework and he is aware of the difficulties of getting things done at sea, I don't think that this has to be a requirement.
I hesitated at your question because I know people feel that way.
When have you been to sea last?
When have you done this or that?
And I think this only comes from...
The people who are going to see, they really don't want to go to see.
And hopefully, most of the ones that are out there are out there for their own curiosity and getting something for their own sake.
So I hope I wishy-washy-ed my way out of that.
But that's a very definite opinion.
I think as long as the modeler is not working in the wilderness,
And of course, that's the task of someone who goes to sea, to be able to explain and describe and report his results.
I don't see why the other person can't read them without having to be sitting on deck while he does it.
That's all I can probably say about that.
OK. Obviously, the computer, of course, in terms of just data classification, data collection, and data availability, the computer has done just wonders for oceanography.
Yet you hear an almost constant complaint somehow the younger oceanographers don't have enough math.
Somehow that their weaknesses in mathematics and...
So a comment as a potential employer.
What do you think is a major weakness that most young oceanographers who come to work in and around you have?
Well of course you'll get a better answer as to how prepared they are from the...
faculty members at the university.
I certainly would say that the professors we had aren't as tough or don't seem to be turning out the thoroughness in individuals that we went through.

I think when we get together and talk and listen to some of the seminars or to talk to the people that are coming out looking for jobs and finding out what they're prepared to do, that there seems to be a little slippage here.
But other than that, there's a whole spectrum of ability in any student at any level.
And I wouldn't say that it's a criticism or even a commonplace attribute that students don't have the math that is necessary, because one wonders what is it that one needs.
It appears today that
you know, that you not only need a complete series of vector equations, but statistics and computers, computer graphics.
There's just so much more to learn and to know than we had, say, even 10 or 20 years ago.
I don't know how they find all the time to put it in.
There's no limit to the
proficiency that one should have in statistics today, and yet that's only one phase.
That's sort of a number crunching attitude.
And when you get into differential equations, there's no limit to how much time you want to spend on becoming proficient in differential equations.
So I find it very difficult to answer that question.
There's no limit to
the proficiency that you would like in all phases of mathematics because of the nature of the interruption in time and space and data, the time series aspects of data.
And I don't see this lacking.
I think that the papers that are evident in the literature show a certainly inadequate mathematical background in their analysis, for my mind.
As a prospective employer,
Is there anything you would like to advise students to do?
Well, I don't know.
I remember when Dr. Fleming.
with that hydrographic office.
He used to tell the people that came to him, put all your books away.
What I need and what you're going to get into isn't in books.
We're going to have to find it out together.
And I think we've advanced beyond that.
I think there are very definite techniques, even in biology, geology, or chemistry, that you need

and these are mathematical techniques and so if I was encouraging anybody in the ocean I would tell them to forget the skin diving aspects or the round the world trips or what have you and to concentrate and then have a good background in mathematics because whatever level that they either end up at or are limited by they will make good use of in the study of the ocean I think one thing that people
aren't prepared for, or don't seem to be prepared for, is the tedious proposal writing.
I think most students that come out have been sheltered by major professors who have gone to the trouble to get grants, and they go out and work, and their initial task is
requires them to jump in and go to work, that's fine.
But very quickly, they will have to come up with a proposal, whether it's government or whether they're working on a grant.
And they will have to explain what it is that they want to do and why.
And this is time consuming.
And a lot of people object to this.
And very few people are trained in it.
And yet, it's one of the facts of life that most people come right into head on.
To be frank, some of them do very poorly.
We talked about mathematics.
Some of them really can't state what it is and why it is that he wants to do it and what it is that he wants to do and why it is significant.
And you find that you have to restructure some of the things that they do.
So it's just like any other decade or century that a good, solid classical scholastic background is needed still.
This exotic science, if you want to call it exotic.
What else are you going to?
That's all I really can say on that.
Okay.
That, again, is enough.
Now, obviously, you're training oceanography, meteorology, marine biology.
It's a very broad education.
Yeah.
Is that one of your suggestions, is that those people receiving an education receive one this broadly construed?
Well, I'm changing my mind on that.
One of the people that had the greatest impact on my career was Dr. Fleming.
And of course, his courses at the university were to give people a broad background rather than a specific one.
But a lot of his staff felt that the specific one really was more important than the broad one.
So there was no conflict there, but less the difference of opinion.
He used to call himself the last general oceanographer.
Well, there are many times that I felt that I inherited that term, that I may be the last general oceanographer.
And in some cases, I thought that might be limiting.
But I find that the people that are specializing are not
are staying with their specialty to the point where they're almost wringing themselves dry.

And yet by being in this specialty, they really don't have the confidence and in many cases the ability to become a program head or to become in the supervisory capacity where he has to address the many facets and the applications and the usefulness of oceanography.
So I have gone in and out of this, the sense that I must specialize in the one that generalization is fine, but it's a very weak spot.
And I'm finally coming back to the point that most of the people that are leading and guiding oceanography today are more the generalists than the specialists.
So I don't object to that term anymore.
In the sense of Dr. Fleming, Wayne Burritt, although the physical type is really
guided oceanography at Oregon State.
Most of his work has been of a general nature rather than a specific rigorous mathematical approach.
And you can go right on down the line.
I even think Stommel is becoming a generalist, although he would probably deny it.
He still has a very unique and a very deep interest in physical oceanography, but I think
In fact, he said in his book that oceanography requires the broad at-sea approach and an understanding of interactions.
So I would have to leave that question in that way.
Any regrets?
Well, they're not regrets as much as if they are sort of incompletions.
I would have liked to have
whetted the appetite of the biologists and the fishery service to become more interested and involved in environmental studies.
There's a good sign that it's coming along now, but it sure didn't come along as quickly as I wanted in the sense that they will.
ask for assistance now, and in many cases are making their own observations.

Whereas when I first came here, we literally had to fight for a time at sea, even on a fishing boat, to ask for 24 hours in a two- or three-month cruise so that you could get a sort of a sampling of just forage organisms to try and assess the food of salmon was considered not
not in the cards, that they just had to get on to their next fishing station.

And I think we're seeing that, like everyone else, I think the meteorologists felt at one time in the early 1900s that they could predict better weather if they had more reporting stations, and they finally got reporting stations all over the country, and today they're saying they still can't forecast.
I think the fishery biologist felt that what he needed was

We're more fishing data and that if he did that he could solve his problem and I think we're getting to the point now where the ships are collecting huge amounts of data and the variability that is environmentally related is becoming sharper and sharper rather than more vague and they're beginning to realize that they're going to have to address this question of the environment really changing the distribution and abundance of organisms.
And so there's nothing new in the sun there.
It's just time.
And other than that, no.
We've had a very interesting phase.
We've worked in an international commission.
We're involved in numerous interdisciplinary programs.
And that's been our approach, to try and get a team of people here.
And I have always had a team.
I have never expanded into the physical group.
We have always had biologists on our team, planktologists.
At one time, we had covered all of the fields of oceanography.
When we had the data buoys, we had an electronic technician to handle our equipment, which is nothing today.
But in those days, he was quite unique.
and a person in primary production, secondary production in descriptive oceanography, theoretical oceanography, and in marine chemistry.
And we had this group, and it should have been expanded two or three times to be a totally effective group.
And instead of that, we were whittled down and had to fight our way like anybody else does through the budgeting system and what have you.
But I think that this is it.
The universities claim, well, we have all these departments.
Therefore, we do integrated studies.
I don't think that's true.
I think you have to get these people at sea, work together.
And I think this is generally Dr. Fleming's philosophy 20, 25 years ago.
And I've tried to make it work here.
And I think I've shown that it would work.
I think I've shown that when you do permit people to do this, you get very interesting results.
But I wouldn't say that it's caught on in many places.
So those are the only two regrets, that we didn't get a commensurate group.
What you want to remember is that NOAA has made up of very roughly 300 fishery biologists, about 6,000 to 7,000 meteorologists, and probably 100 bona fide oceanographers.
And so what we're trying to do is
Fisheries people realize that they're working in the ocean, but they have other requirements for their money.
The meteorologists realize the ocean changes the atmosphere, but they've been plotting weather maps for years.
They don't want it.
And I would hope that the three stand as a triad, and they all.
That would be my wish for oceanography, is that there is a coordinated group that
puts the pieces together.
I don't object to the universities studying anything they want at any time and any place.
But to just put it together and let it rest there for 10 or 15 years because there's nobody that is working on the puzzle that that's a piece of is a crime.
And I would like to see something in the order of 2,000 or 3,000 oceanographers.
And I think that the country would be amazed at what is going on in the ocean and how it does apply to their livelihood and their climate.
So if that was a wish, then that's what I would like.
In fact, I wrote when Bob White came into the system.
We were in interior and joined ESSA, which became NOAA.
I told him, you know, take care of your oceanographers.
But he certainly was unable to do very much in that area.
So I have no complaints.
That's what I would wish would happen.
Is there anything you'd like to add to the tape?
Any comments you'd like to make?
Which questions missed?
No, I think that one thing that I would like to see more of that I don't think really you touched on, and that is international cooperation.
And we touched on it just with the Japanese, not with other groups.
Don Hood at the University of Alaska has done just great work in trying to get
the Soviet Union, Canada, Japan, and Korea are interested in studies in the Bering Sea.
And he's had some success at this.
And I find this rather lacking in other areas.
There's a lot of one-on-one.
You have a friend that is in Japan, and you write a project together, and you study it.
I'm talking about large-scale, multidisciplinary, integrated investigations by countries.
that have a finite time period and a specific objective.
I would like to see more of this.
We had some of it in the INPFC.
We get a lot of it here at the center.
The Soviets will come through, they're fishing Hague, and they begin to realize that Hague fluctuates quite a bit.
And just a few months ago we gave an extensive talk on the environment of the Hague.
We haven't discussed the environment in the INPF of salmon.
We're dealing with the environment of pollock and ground fish along the coast.
And I think that the fisheries group deal with this, but they don't deal with it.
They deal with it at the level of fishery oceanographers, someone that's used to correlating temperature with fish or something like that.
We don't really deal here with the oceanographers who have studied it as a system and how it changes.
And this is what Don Hood has done.
Now, I don't see very much of this all the way down the coast here on that scale.
I wouldn't take away the fact that they are aware of foreign scientists and they travel back and forth.
But I don't consider IDOE in this category and some of the other programs.
But if there was one person I think that has taken an approach that I think is necessary, it's that.
Because I think
What we are going to need and will get, certainly, in five or 10 years is sort of a Pacific commission, sort of something like the ICs in the Atlantic.
In fact, we jokingly call it Pisces, which, of course, is fish, you see.
But we're going to have to know what is going on in the ocean, why it goes on, what effect it has on the biota, and how the biota interacts.
When the Albert Corps come up to the salmon front, or they eat the salmon, or the salmon run away, and what is the front that they will or will not go beyond?
And if they do this, what happens to the seals?
And what happens to everything else?
This whole system has to be really laid out.
And it can only be done by some kind of an international Pacific commission.
And that's all I tried to do here on a very, very small scale.
And I think it will come.
I think it's necessary.
But it will.
It will take a lot of planning, and hopefully it won't get bogged down in administration.
But I guess that's another wish for the future that I would like to see.
So other than that, nothing.
